{"action": "input", "code": "def expand_target_grid(target_grid: np.ndarray, side_length: float) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    Given a target grid and a side length, this function expands the target grid proportionally by the side length times and returns the expanded grid.\n    \"\"\"\n    return np.repeat(np.repeat(target_grid, side_length, axis=0), side_length, axis=1)\ndef find_yellow_pixels(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> Tuple[int, int, int, int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Given an input grid, this function finds the first and last yellow pixels and returns their coordinates as a tuple (x1, y1, x2, y2).\n    \"\"\"\n    n = input_grid.shape[0]\n    x1, y1, x2, y2 = (n, n, -1, -1)\n    for i in range(n):\n        for j in range(n):\n            if input_grid[i][j] == yellow:\n                x1 = min(x1, i)\n                y1 = min(y1, j)\n                x2 = max(x2, i)\n                y2 = max(y2, j)\n    return (x1, y1, x2, y2)\ndef main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    In the input, you should see a n*n grid with multiple color pixels.\n    \"\"\"\n    x1, y1, x2, y2 = find_yellow_pixels(input_grid)\n    ans_grid = input_grid[x1:x2 + 1, y1:y2 + 1]\n    input_grid[x1:x2 + 1, y1:y2 + 1] = black\n    minx, miny, maxx, maxy = update_min_max_coordinates(input_grid)\n    target_grid = input_grid[minx:maxx + 1, miny:maxy + 1]\n    kind, cnt = count_non_black_pixels(ans_grid)\n    side_length = math.sqrt(cnt / kind)\n    target_grid = expand_target_grid(target_grid, side_length)\n    ans = copy_target_grid_to_ans_grid(ans_grid, target_grid)\n    return ans\ndef copy_target_grid_to_ans_grid(ans_grid: np.ndarray, target_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    Given an ans_grid and a target_grid, this function finds the first non-black pixel (x, y) in ans_grid and copies target_grid as grid to this position.\n    \"\"\"\n    x, y = np.where(ans_grid != black)\n    ans_grid[x[0]:x[0] + target_grid.shape[0], y[0]:y[0] + target_grid.shape[1]] = target_grid\n    return ans_grid\ndef count_non_black_pixels(ans_grid: np.ndarray) -> Tuple[int, int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Given an input grid, this function counts the number of unique non-black pixels and their total count and returns them as a tuple (kind, cnt).\n    \"\"\"\n    kind = len(np.unique(ans_grid)) - 1\n    cnt = np.count_nonzero(ans_grid != black)\n    return (kind, cnt)\ndef update_min_max_coordinates(grid: np.ndarray) -> Tuple[int, int, int, int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Given an input grid, this function returns the smallest x, the smallest y, the largest x, and the largest y coordinates of non-black pixels as a tuple (minx, miny, maxx, maxy).\n    \"\"\"\n    n = grid.shape[0]\n    minx, miny, maxx, maxy = (n, n, -1, -1)\n    for i in range(n):\n        for j in range(n):\n            if grid[i][j] != black:\n                minx = min(minx, i)\n                miny = min(miny, j)\n                maxx = max(maxx, i)\n                maxy = max(maxy, j)\n    return (minx, miny, maxx, maxy)", "user_code": "import math\ndef main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    In the input, you should see a n*n grid with multiple color pixels.\n    \"\"\"\n    x1,y1,x2,y2 = `From left to right, top to bottom, traverse the entire grid, find the first yellow pixel (x1, y1), the last yellow pixel (x2, y2), return (x1, y1, x2, y2)`(input_grid)\n    ans_grid = input_grid[x1:x2+1,y1:y2+1]\n    input_grid[x1:x2+1,y1:y2+1] = black\n    minx, miny, maxx, maxy = `Define four variables (minx, miny, maxx, maxy) as the smallest x, the smallest y, the largest x, and the largest y. Traverse all the pixels in the new grid, if a pixel (x, y) is not black, use the pixel to update the above four variables`(input_grid)\n    target_grid = input_grid[minx:maxx+1,miny:maxy+1]\n    kind,cnt = `Traverse all pixels in ansgrid, count the kind and quantity of non-black pixels, and return (kind, cnt)`(ans_grid)\n    side_length = math.sqrt(cnt/kind)\n    target_grid = `Expand the ta